1) The water cycle is interconnected because it is a continuous process of evaporation, condensation, precipitation, runoff, infiltration, and groundwater flow. Each stage is important in maintaining the balance of water on Earth. Evaporation is the process by which water changes from liquid to gas, while condensation is the opposite process where water vapor turns into liquid droplets. Precipitation occurs when these droplets fall back down to Earth as rain or snow. Runoff happens when excess water flows over land surfaces and into rivers or streams. Infiltration refers to the movement of water through soil layers until it reaches groundwater reserves below ground level. Finally, groundwater flow involves the movement of underground water towards bodies of water such as lakes or oceans. All these stages work together to ensure that there is enough fresh water available for all living things on our planet.

2) Each stage plays a crucial role in sustaining life on Earth:
    - Evaporation helps regulate temperature by cooling off hot areas like deserts during summer months;
    - Condensation provides moisture needed for plants’ growth;
    - Precipitation replenishes surface waters like rivers and lakes;
    - Runoff carries nutrients away from agricultural fields back into natural ecosystems;
    - Infiltration recharges aquifers used for drinking
